  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA126-kiḷavi">itu poruḷ valitta neñciṉait talaivaṉ neruṅkic celavaḻuṅkiyatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is how he prevented going, directed to [his] heart that was striving for wealth.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA126">
<l>            paiṅkāy nalliṭa morīiya ceṅkāyk</l>
<l>            karuṅkaḷi yīntiṉ veṇpuṟak kaḷari</l>
<l>            yiṭunī ṟāṭiya kaṭunaṭai yorutta</l>
<l>            lāṭpeṟa ṉacaii nāṭcuram vilaṅkit</l>
<l>            tuṇaitarum vampalark kāṇā tacciṉam </l>
<l>            paṉaikkāṉ ṟāṟum pāḻnāṭ ṭatta</l>
<l>            miṟantucey poruḷu miṉpan tarumeṉi</l>
<l>            ṉiḷamaiyiṟ ciṟanta vaḷamaiyu millai</l>
<l>            yiḷamai kaḻinta piṉṟai vaḷamai</l>
<l>            kāman tarutalu miṉṟē yataṉā </l>
<l>            ṉillāp poruṭpiṇic cēṟi</l>
<l>            vallē neñcam vāykkaniṉ viṉaiyē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent3">If they say wealth too gives joy</l>
<l rend="indent2">that is made traversing the road through the ruined lands,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the quick-gaited male that bathed in the dust from<note place="foot">The formulaic parallels of this passage in NA 41.2 and 302.8 show that here, strangely, a phrase has been broken up over two lines. Thus <term xml:lang="ta">iṭu</term> at the beginning of the line in fact connects with <term xml:lang="ta">kaḷari</term> of the previous line as a sort of ablative conjunction, without verbal force.</note> the</l>
<l rend="indent2">white-backed saline soil near the date palm with black toddy from the</l>
<l rend="indent2">red unripe fruits abandoned in a good place with fresh unripe fruits(?)<note place="foot">What is the point of the description given in the first two lines and how exactly to construe them?</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">without seeing strangers that bring companions,</l>
<l rend="indent">alleviates that anger by attacking a palmyra tree,</l>
<l>there is no prosperity superior to youth</l>
<l>and, after youth has passed by, prosperity</l>
<l>doesn't bring [back] desire.</l>
<l rend="indent4">Therefore,</l>
<l>you want to go enticed by unstable wealth.</l>
<l>Speedily, heart, may your work be achieved.</l>
        </lg>
